[DhtmlXQ_comment0]mg fork skewer pin explained ||A fork occurs when 2 pieces are threatened with capture with one move.||There are 2 forks in this example that I created.[/DhtmlXQ_comment0]
[DhtmlXQ_comment1]Fork number 1||There is a fork with the cannon in this example.||Red is effectively threatening to capture the black chariot with C3-2 and the black horse with C3+3. If either one runs away, the other gets captured.||For example, the chariot is worth more...so...[/DhtmlXQ_comment1]
[DhtmlXQ_comment1_1]Fork number 2||This is also a fork by the horse. ||The two cannons are waiting to be captured with this horse move.||One runs away and the other gets caught.[/DhtmlXQ_comment1_1]
[DhtmlXQ_comment1_3]Material is gained.[/DhtmlXQ_comment1_3]
[DhtmlXQ_comment2_1]Fork number 3 by the red chariot.||One runs away, the other gets caught.[/DhtmlXQ_comment2_1]
[DhtmlXQ_comment3_1]Skewer!||This is a skewer. Red is performing a check on the king...[/DhtmlXQ_comment3_1]
[DhtmlXQ_comment3_2]...which must move away, thereby exposing the horse. ||The horse has been skewered...and...[/DhtmlXQ_comment3_2]
[DhtmlXQ_comment3_3]...captured[/DhtmlXQ_comment3_3]
[DhtmlXQ_comment4_1]Skewer...but bear with me...as I try to explain the pin.[/DhtmlXQ_comment4_1]
[DhtmlXQ_comment4_2]Let us say that black makes this move instead of. This would be a pin now. ||If the black cannon moves away, there would be a check. ||The piece being pinned may be protected and have a root or it may be unprotected or rootless.[/DhtmlXQ_comment4_2]
